<p>It's the most common question we get asked, and the honest answer is frustrating: it depends. Not a particularly satisfying response when you're trying to plan your maintenance calendar, but the reality is that the right cleaning frequency varies significantly based on where your boat is moored, how often you use it, what type of hull coating you have, and what time of year it is.</p>

<p>That said, we've cleaned enough hulls across Brixham, Torquay, and Dartmouth to have developed some reliable rules of thumb. Here's what we've learned.</p>

<h2>The Three-Month Baseline</h2>

<p>For most recreational sailing yachts in South Devon, a quarterly clean (every 3 months) provides a solid baseline of hull maintenance. This frequency catches fouling during its early development stages — before barnacles have fully hardened, before algae has bonded to your antifouling, and before the accumulated growth starts measurably affecting your boat's performance.</p>

<p>A quarterly schedule aligns roughly with seasonal transitions: a spring clean in March or April removes winter biofilm and prepares your hull for the season; a midsummer clean in June or July tackles the peak fouling growth; an autumn clean in September or October clears the summer's accumulation before lay-up; and if your boat stays in the water over winter, a January clean prevents compacted silt from hardening.</p>

<h2>When Quarterly Isn't Enough</h2>

<p>Some situations demand more frequent attention. In our experience, the following factors push the optimal frequency from quarterly toward bi-monthly or even more:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Swing moorings on the River Dart.</strong> Stationary vessels in the Dart's estuarine waters accumulate fouling significantly faster than marina-berthed boats. The combination of no water movement, high nutrient levels from Dartmoor runoff, and fine silt creates conditions where a hull can progress from clean to moderately fouled in 6-8 weeks during summer. We typically recommend bi-monthly cleaning for Dart moorings.</li>
  <li><strong>Vessels used infrequently.</strong> This is counterintuitive, but boats that rarely move foul faster than boats that are used regularly. Movement through the water creates flow across the hull that discourages fouling settlement. A yacht that sits on its mooring for months between outings is essentially a stationary substrate for marine organisms.</li>
  <li><strong>Older antifouling coatings.</strong> Antifouling paint loses its biocidal effectiveness over time. A hull with 18-month-old ablative antifouling will foul faster than a hull with a fresh 3-month-old coating. If you're extending the interval between repaints, you'll likely need to increase your cleaning frequency to compensate.</li>
  <li><strong>Warm water berths.</strong> Biological activity correlates directly with water temperature. Boats in Torquay, which benefits from slightly warmer English Riviera temperatures, may experience faster fouling during summer than boats in more exposed harbours further along the coast.</li>
</ul>

<h2>When Quarterly Is More Than Enough</h2>

<p>Conversely, some owners can get away with less frequent cleaning without meaningful consequences:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Boats used weekly or more.</strong> If you're out on the water every weekend, the hull movement alone discourages some fouling settlement. Combined with fresh antifouling paint, you might find that two cleans per year (spring and late summer) is sufficient.</li>
  <li><strong>New antifouling applications.</strong> A hull freshly painted with high-quality ablative antifouling can often go 4-6 months before the first clean is needed, particularly if the boat is used regularly.</li>
  <li><strong>Hard antifouling paints.</strong> Hard (non-ablative) antifouling coatings work differently to ablative types and can sometimes tolerate longer intervals between cleans. However, they accumulate fouling on their surface more visibly and require more mechanical effort to clean when the time comes.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Location-Specific Recommendations</h2>

<p>Based on our experience across South Devon's three main marinas, here's our general guidance:</p>

<p><strong>Brixham Marina:</strong> Quarterly cleaning is appropriate for most berth holders. The harbour's nutrient-rich waters (driven by the commercial fishing fleet) produce consistent fouling, but the enclosed marina environment is relatively predictable. We recommend the Essential plan (4 cleans per year) for most Brixham boats.</p>

<p><strong>Torquay Marina:</strong> Quarterly to bi-monthly, depending on vessel size and usage. Larger motor vessels that sit idle between occasional use should lean toward bi-monthly during the summer season. Actively sailed yachts can generally manage on quarterly cleans. Torquay's 24/7 lock gate access makes scheduling easier than at other marinas.</p>

<p><strong>Dartmouth (River Dart):</strong> Bi-monthly is our strong recommendation for most river-moored vessels. The Dart's estuarine conditions accelerate fouling beyond what most open-harbour marinas produce. Boats on swing moorings should strongly consider the Premium plan (6 cleans per year). Only infrequently used boats in Darthaven's most sheltered inner berths might manage on quarterly cleaning alone.</p>

<h2>The Cost of Getting It Wrong</h2>

<p>Cleaning too infrequently is more expensive than cleaning too frequently. That sounds obvious, but many boat owners underestimate the compounding costs of neglect. A hull that's allowed to develop heavy fouling requires a longer cleaning session (higher cost per clean), causes more antifouling wear during removal (bringing forward your next repaint), wastes fuel through increased drag in the meantime, and may require harder brush types that are less gentle on your coating.</p>

<p>By contrast, cleaning a hull with only light biofilm takes less time, removes growth that hasn't yet bonded permanently, and preserves your antifouling for longer. The marginal cost of one extra clean per year is almost always less than the cumulative cost of one fewer clean.</p>

